For me it was about conserving my energy.  I cannot give her the peace she needs.  I cannot force her to get over and deal with the things she needs to.  But I just simply could not allow myself to continue to be hurt by the side affect of her pain.  She was emotionally and physically abusive to me, and was emotionally and physically abused in her own childhood.  I was adopted when I was around 3 or so, and everyone made sure to tell me how thankful and appreciative I needed to be that they picked up this discarded little orphan, that I was &quot;specially chosen&quot;.  That combination dorked my head up for years.  But I forgive her for how she was to me because I know that deep down she let herself down.  She thought she would be a great mother and she was faced with her own inadequacies and her own ghosts.  Instead of dealing with them and healing, she took it all out on me.  Mind you I'm not making excuses for her; in the end she will be accountable for her own actions. I just understand what a tormented and messed up person she is, so when she says and does things that would have once caused me pain I refuse to let myself be pained by it now.  I say &quot;well, there she goes again&quot; and emotionally remove myself from it.<br>
<br>
It helps though that my Father was man enough to come to me and broach the subject of my childhood and he let me get it all out and we are strong and loving now.  I am also surrounded by very loving and caring people in my life.  My mother loves me, she's just too messed up in the head to treat me and act towards me how I wished she could have.  I can't let my life or actions be defined by that anymore.  What's different about my situation is that my mother is very passive-aggresive.  She digs and jabs with a tone of &quot;I love you and your daughters so much I do anything for you even though you hurt me so...&quot;  And she has done that so long she honestly believes herself to be the victim of my thoughtlessness, creating imagined slights and hurts that don't exist for anyone in the world but for her.  The few things I have done that I know genuinely were hurtful I did my best to make amends, and took responsibility for them, but in the grand scheme of things it was growing-pains kind of stuff that in no way accounted for her sense of martrydom to this day.  She's loony to put it bluntly, and how can you hate someone who isn't all there?  It's like banging your head against the wall.<br>
<br>
As I said, it's not as simple as &quot;I just don't let it bother me anymore&quot;... it took years of self-help after years of self-destruction to get to this place.     <p>--------------------------------<br>
